###what route it will produce

This is a classic Rails interview question.
Letâ€™s break it slowly and clearly, then list all routes produced.

Code
resources :users do
  resources :posts, shallow: true
end

ğŸ”¹ What does shallow: true mean?

ğŸ‘‰ Collection routes stay nested
ğŸ‘‰ Member routes become non-nested

In simple words:

Routes that need user_id â†’ stay nested

Routes that operate on a specific post (:id) â†’ become shallow

ğŸ§© Generated Routes (TOTAL: 8)
ğŸ”¸ User Routes (7 standard REST routes)
GET    /users          â†’ users#index
GET    /users/new      â†’ users#new
POST   /users          â†’ users#create
GET    /users/:id      â†’ users#show
GET    /users/:id/edit â†’ users#edit
PATCH  /users/:id      â†’ users#update
DELETE /users/:id      â†’ users#destroy

ğŸ”¸ Post Routes (Shallow)
âœ… Nested (collection-level)

These require user_id because they create or list posts for a user.

GET  /users/:user_id/posts     â†’ posts#index
POST /users/:user_id/posts     â†’ posts#create
GET  /users/:user_id/posts/new â†’ posts#new

âœ… Shallow (member-level)

These work on a specific post, so user_id is NOT needed.

GET    /posts/:id      â†’ posts#show
GET    /posts/:id/edit â†’ posts#edit
PATCH  /posts/:id      â†’ posts#update
DELETE /posts/:id      â†’ posts#destroy

ğŸ“Š Summary Table
Type	Route Example
Nested	/users/:user_id/posts
Shallow	/posts/:id
ğŸ§  Why use shallow: true?
âŒ Without shallow
/users/1/posts/99/edit

âœ… With shallow
/posts/99/edit


âœ” Cleaner URLs
âœ” Less redundancy
âœ” Still keeps logical nesting

ğŸ”¥ Interview One-Liner

"shallow: true keeps collection routes nested under the parent resource but makes member routes independent, resulting in cleaner and more maintainable URLs."

